  <a id="1723" href="TypeTopology.DecidabilityOfNonContinuity.html#1723" class="Function">claim₄</a> <a id="1730" class="Symbol">:</a> <a id="1732" href="MLTT.Negation.html#611" class="Function">is-decidable</a> <a id="1745" class="Symbol">((</a><a id="1747" href="TypeTopology.DecidabilityOfNonContinuity.html#1747" class="Bound">n</a> <a id="1749" class="Symbol">:</a> <a id="1751" href="MLTT.Natural-Numbers-Type.html#96" class="Datatype">ℕ</a><a id="1752" class="Symbol">)</a> <a id="1754" class="Symbol">→</a> <a id="1756" href="MLTT.Negation.html#305" class="Function Operator">¬</a> <a id="1758" class="Symbol">(</a><a id="1759" href="TypeTopology.DecidabilityOfNonContinuity.html#1210" class="Function">A</a> <a id="1761" class="Symbol">(</a><a id="1762" href="Notation.CanonicalMap.html#360" class="Field">ι</a> <a id="1764" href="TypeTopology.DecidabilityOfNonContinuity.html#1747" class="Bound">n</a><a id="1765" class="Symbol">)))</a>
  <a id="1771" href="TypeTopology.DecidabilityOfNonContinuity.html#1723" class="Function">claim₄</a> <a id="1778" class="Symbol">=</a> <a id="1780" href="NotionsOfDecidability.Decidable.html#410" class="Function">map-decidable</a> <a id="1794" href="TypeTopology.DecidabilityOfNonContinuity.html#1611" class="Function">claim₃</a> <a id="1801" href="TypeTopology.DecidabilityOfNonContinuity.html#1448" class="Function">claim₂</a> <a id="1808" href="TypeTopology.DecidabilityOfNonContinuity.html#1374" class="Function">claim₁</a>

<a id="1816" class="Markup">\end{code}</a><a id="1826" class="Background">

Omitting the inclusion function, or coercion,

   ι : ℕ → ℕ∞,

a map f : ℕ∞ → ℕ is called continuous iff

   ∃ m. ∀ n ≥ m. f n ＝ f ∞,

where m and n range over the natural numbers.

The negation of this statement is equivalent to

   ∀ m. ¬ ∀ n ≥ m. f n ＝ f ∞.

We can implement ∀ y ≥ x. A y as ∀ x. A (max x y), so that the
continuity of f amounts to

   ∃ m. ∀ n. f (max m n) ＝ f ∞,

and its negation to

   ∀ m. ¬ ∀ n. f (max m n) ＝ f ∞.

Because we are going to prove facts about the negation of continuity,
it doesn&#39;t matter whether we define the notion with ∃ or Σ, and we
choose the latter for convenience.

</a><a id="2443" class="Markup">\begin{code}</a>

<a id="continuous"></a><a id="2457" href="TypeTopology.DecidabilityOfNonContinuity.html#2457" class="Function">continuous</a> <a id="2468" class="Symbol">:</a> <a id="2470" class="Symbol">(</a><a id="2471" href="CoNaturals.GenericConvergentSequence.html#1395" class="Function">ℕ∞</a> <a id="2474" class="Symbol">→</a> <a id="2476" href="MLTT.Natural-Numbers-Type.html#96" class="Datatype">ℕ</a><a id="2477" class="Symbol">)</a> <a id="2479" class="Symbol">→</a> <a id="2481" href="Agda.Primitive.html#915" class="Primitive">𝓤₀</a> <a id="2484" href="MLTT.Universes.html#394" class="Function Operator">̇</a>
